Hi Necross, I somehow bypassed this problem at that time, maybe I changed either the photo compiler or NeuralNetwork.proto.
Now I just came across exactly the same problem again, when I tried to update my proto files with the latest version.

Here is how to reproduce this bug:
First, get the protobuf 3.6.0 from https://github.com/google/protobuf/releases.
Then simply run
```
./configure
make
make install
```
To compile the proto files in coremltools/mlmodel/format, I just ran
```
mkdir build
./protoc --proto_path=format/ --objc_out=build/ format/*.proto
```
in `coremltools/mlmodel/`

And the compiled subclasses of NeuralNetwork with weights (including `ConvolutionLayerParams`, `InnerProductLayerParams`, `EmbeddingLayerParams`, ...) contain the following properties:
```
@dynamic hasBias;
@dynamic hasWeights, weights;
@dynamic hasBias, bias;
```
which cause the above conflict.

My point is that the reason of such conflict is the naming mechanism of the objc protoc compiler.
In the current version of `NeuralNetwork.proto`, the bias flag is named as 'hasBias', but there's another variance named bias (it's type is `WeightParams`). So the compiler generates a `hasBias` bool flag for `bias`, which has exactly the same name as the existed 'hasBias' in the original proto message.

Also, this conflict do not exists in cpp (as in `coremltools/mlmodel/build/format/`), because the cpp proto compiler uses underline in naming so these names are different.

So the general proposal is that we should either change the name 'hasBias' in `NeuralNetwork.proto`, or just delete it, because protoc will generate this flag for us.

And I found that in the old version of `NeuralNetwork.proto` I used, it uses the name `ifhasBias ` instead of `hasBias`. I just cannot remember if this was modified by myself or it is from the previous version of mlmodel two months ago.

```
    /**
     * Flag to specify whether a bias is to be added or not.
     */
    bool ifhasBias = 70;

    /**
     * Weights associated with this layer.
     * If convolution (``isDeconvolution == false``), weights have the shape
     * ``[outputChannels, kernelChannels, kernelHeight, kernelWidth]``, where kernelChannels == inputChannels / nGroups
     * If deconvolution (``isDeconvolution == true``) weights have the shape
     * ``[kernelChannels, outputChannels / nGroups, kernelHeight, kernelWidth]``, where kernelChannels == inputChannels
     */
    WeightParams weights = 90;
    WeightParams bias = 91; /// Must be of size [outputChannels].
```

The bool flag is named 'ifhasBias', while the weight parameter is named 'bias', so after compiling into objc, the class `ConvolutionLayerParams` has the following three properties:

```
@dynamic ifhasBias;
@dynamic hasWeights, weights;
@dynamic hasBias, bias;
```

There's no conflicts.
I think this problem is obvious and I'm just wandering why no one propose this.

