Hummm, not really, this is the code:

```
        if (self.closing_address == caller_address) {
            throw;
        }
```

It only says "do not allow for the closing party to call updateTransfer", but it does not say "allow only the counter party to call close". Without ordering of messages that is not acceptable since the closing party might just call the `updateTransfer` using a different account and supply a forged transfer.

I believe this was set up this way to allow for third parties to call close, . Btw, that check and the [modifier](https://github.com/czepluch/raiden/blob/7e9189f178022070d0769869e7a620e5a8e2a580/raiden/smart_contracts/NettingChannelLibrary.sol#L278) are doing the same thing.

```
[10]
input: for_each={'i': range(1)}
task:
run:
	echo I am ${i}
	sleep ${3+i}

[20]
input: for_each={'i': range(2)}
task:
run:
	echo I am step 2 ${i}
	sleep ${5+i}
```

would fail under fork mode.

